      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771555280015,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive 1: each component scale? QPS & MEM + CAP",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive 1: each component scale? QPS & MEM + CAP",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "bBuHiEv0XSBGoGPMM-a6V",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2631.343621766326,
      "y": 4221.6843611037,
      "width": 1013.2791748046875,
      "height": 275,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3E",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1110952864,
      "version": 944,
      "versionNonce": 1482357344,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771559455994,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive 2: add/ remove friends\n\n- add friend: WS conn handler needs to be updated so it can subscribe to new friend's pub/ sub channel\n- we can assume that the app registered a call back on the mobile client whenver a new friend is added\n- the CB upon invocation\n    1. sends a message to the WS server\n    2. it needs to subscribe to the new friend's channel (server)\n    3. can grab the new friend's loc & timestamp from cache\n    4. send back details to client\n* likewise for friend removal\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive 2: add/ remove friends\n\n- add friend: WS conn handler needs to be updated so it can subscribe to new friend's pub/ sub channel\n- we can assume that the app registered a call back on the mobile client whenver a new friend is added\n- the CB upon invocation\n    1. sends a message to the WS server\n    2. it needs to subscribe to the new friend's channel (server)\n    3. can grab the new friend's loc & timestamp from cache\n    4. send back details to client\n* likewise for friend removal\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "_JkV6A-f-in6rn_NurL1E",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2633.9412377260583,
      "y": 4550.086146496446,
      "width": 1245.0791015625,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3F",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2092700576,
      "version": 1208,
      "versionNonce": 254039648,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771560015319,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive 3: users with many friends (edge case)\n- worth discussing whether many friends can cause performance hotspot in our design\n- assume here that there is a hard cap of friends a person can have (FB has cap of 5000 friends for e.g.)\n    this is coz friendship is bidirectional & not like follower model (worry about fan out issues)\n- even with thousand of friends, pub/ sub subscribers will be scattered among many WS servers in the cluster (1: N subscribers)\n- update load will spread among them & would not overwhelm a single instance",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive 3: users with many friends (edge case)\n- worth discussing whether many friends can cause performance hotspot in our design\n- assume here that there is a hard cap of friends a person can have (FB has cap of 5000 friends for e.g.)\n    this is coz friendship is bidirectional & not like follower model (worry about fan out issues)\n- even with thousand of friends, pub/ sub subscribers will be scattered among many WS servers in the cluster (1: N subscribers)\n- update load will spread among them & would not overwhelm a single instance",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Q3bxsP0jnIwN_cv66nIRj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2625.0747964093603,
      "y": 4786.783863656357,
      "width": 946.639404296875,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3G",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1706048096,
      "version": 1426,
      "versionNonce": 1674393184,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771560669395,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive 4: nearby random person?? (extra)\nwhat if we wanted additional functinality to see other randos who arent my friends?\n\n1 way is to add pool of pub/sub channels by geo hash (channel is created for each grid)\n- anyone within the same grid subscribes to the same channel\n- take grid 9q8znd for e.g.\n    1. when user 2 updates location\n    2. it publishes not jsut to friends, but people within the same geohash grid\n    3. anyone nearby who subscribes to the channel, will receive the udpate\n*to handle ppl who are close to the border of the grid, every WS server (client) can subscribe to\n    not just its current grid, but surrounding grids.\n*it would not publish to all surrounding grids tho",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive 4: nearby random person?? (extra)\nwhat if we wanted additional functinality to see other randos who arent my friends?\n\n1 way is to add pool of pub/sub channels by geo hash (channel is created for each grid)\n- anyone within the same grid subscribes to the same channel\n- take grid 9q8znd for e.g.\n    1. when user 2 updates location\n    2. it publishes not jsut to friends, but people within the same geohash grid\n    3. anyone nearby who subscribes to the channel, will receive the udpate\n*to handle ppl who are close to the border of the grid, every WS server (client) can subscribe to\n    not just its current grid, but surrounding grids.\n*it would not publish to all surrounding grids tho",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "hXtDEgC_n8BL-iGf2NjdB",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -869.5466691442615,
      "y": 3314.9389463004272,
      "width": 797.3394165039062,
      "height": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3H",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1641916320,
      "version": 256,
      "versionNonce": 1992006240,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771553008670,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Notice that:\n- even though this is update of once every 30s, the client still wants to\nmaintain WS connection with the websocket servers\n- sharing of state is via the redis pub sub(upon update) & redis cache (upon init)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Notice that:\n- even though this is update of once every 30s, the client still wants to\nmaintain WS connection with the websocket servers\n- sharing of state is via the redis pub sub(upon update) & redis cache (upon init)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "pJhZhEVmDPUpMD4sqDVog",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -749.6713998213005,
      "y": 4242.152874934979,
      "width": 827.9393920898438,
      "height": 275,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3I",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 31222368,
      "version": 1054,
      "versionNonce": 1158430304,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771552829744,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Before going into deep dive, i actually have some questions:\n- so what if a user breaks connection?\n    => from what i understand, the user makes a conn with the WS server\n    => the WS server then subscribes to the redis topic? (the ones that are friends)\n    => when friend updates, it publihshes & these subscribers get update\n    => i guess when no update it gets from cache, and if its within TTL it exists\n    => then if its after TTL, loc expires & friend will assume its offline\n\n    => qns here is then how does the guy who just came online,\n        know which topic is where?\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Before going into deep dive, i actually have some questions:\n- so what if a user breaks connection?\n    => from what i understand, the user makes a conn with the WS server\n    => the WS server then subscribes to the redis topic? (the ones that are friends)\n    => when friend updates, it publihshes & these subscribers get update\n    => i guess when no update it gets from cache, and if its within TTL it exists\n    => then if its after TTL, loc expires & friend will assume its offline\n\n    => qns here is then how does the guy who just came online,\n        know which topic is where?\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "6foNtKgOevN8_z4NSLkzU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 133.86711859685693,
      "y": 4250.752188861872,
      "width": 1060.5194091796875,
      "height": 1000,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3J",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 858930784,
      "version": 1975,
      "versionNonce": 819459680,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771555341339,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "API servers:\n- normal methods to scale RESTFul API tiers\n- stateless servers need auto scale the clusters base on CPU usage,\nload, I/O\n\nWebsocket servers:\n- note that these are stateful\n- when removing existing nodes, b4 a node can be removed, all connections\non node needs to be allowed to drain\n- we mark node as \"draining\" at LB to ensure no new web socket conns will\nbe routed to the draining server\n- once existing conns are closed (or after reasonably long wait), server can be removed\n- effective auto-scaling of stateful servers is the job of good load balancers, msot\ncloud LB handles this job well\n\nuser DB:\n2 sets of data\n1. user profiles (userId, username, profile URL etc.)\n2. friendships\n\n- note that the current design will not fit in single r/s DB instance\n- horizontally scalable by sharding based on user ID => common\n- side note: user & friendship datasets will likely be manged by a dedicated team,\n                available via an internal API instead of querying the DB directly to fetch\n                user & friendship-related data => not much diff in perf\n\nlocation cache:\n- redis to cache coz can set TTL on each key (but can choose any other KV MEM store that can set TTL)\n- TTL renewed on every update\n- this puts a cap on max MEM used\n    - each loc takes no more than 100 bytes => 100b * 10 mil = 1 GB\n    - single redis instance is fine\n- but QPS is issue\n    - 10 mil active users/ 30 secs = ~300k req/s\n    - very high even for modern servers\n    - luckily, ez to shard => base on userId\n- to improve availability, we can dup loc data on each shard to a standby node\n    - if 1 node fails, shard can quickly be promoted to minimize down time\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "API servers:\n- normal methods to scale RESTFul API tiers\n- stateless servers need auto scale the clusters base on CPU usage,\nload, I/O\n\nWebsocket servers:\n- note that these are stateful\n- when removing existing nodes, b4 a node can be removed, all connections\non node needs to be allowed to drain\n- we mark node as \"draining\" at LB to ensure no new web socket conns will\nbe routed to the draining server\n- once existing conns are closed (or after reasonably long wait), server can be removed\n- effective auto-scaling of stateful servers is the job of good load balancers, msot\ncloud LB handles this job well\n\nuser DB:\n2 sets of data\n1. user profiles (userId, username, profile URL etc.)\n2. friendships\n\n- note that the current design will not fit in single r/s DB instance\n- horizontally scalable by sharding based on user ID => common\n- side note: user & friendship datasets will likely be manged by a dedicated team,\n                available via an internal API instead of querying the DB directly to fetch\n                user & friendship-related data => not much diff in perf\n\nlocation cache:\n- redis to cache coz can set TTL on each key (but can choose any other KV MEM store that can set TTL)\n- TTL renewed on every update\n- this puts a cap on max MEM used\n    - each loc takes no more than 100 bytes => 100b * 10 mil = 1 GB\n    - single redis instance is fine\n- but QPS is issue\n    - 10 mil active users/ 30 secs = ~300k req/s\n    - very high even for modern servers\n    - luckily, ez to shard => base on userId\n- to improve availability, we can dup loc data on each shard to a standby node\n    - if 1 node fails, shard can quickly be promoted to minimize down time\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "vb42Qxxc-DoZ8oHoFhHv_",
      "type": "text",
