      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "client init:\n1. client establish new WS conn with WS server instance => each conn is long running, small MEM\n2. client immediately sends curr loc & server performs following task in conn handler fn\na. update user loc in loc cache\nb. saves loc i na variable of the conn handler for subsequent calcs\nc. load all user's friends from DB\nd. make a batched request ot the loc cache to fetch all locs. becoz TTL was set on\n    each entry that matches inactivity, we can tell if friend is on/off line\ne. for each loc returned by cache, server computes the dist. between the user & friend\n    if its within range, it will return client with the (lat,lng,timestmap)\nf. for each  friend, server subscribes to the friend's channel in the redis pub/sub server\n(creation of new channel is cheap, user subscribes to all active & inactive friends; inactive friends\n    only take up a smalle amt of MEM on redis pub/sub server but will not consumer any CPU/IO (since no updates))",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "client init:\n1. client establish new WS conn with WS server instance => each conn is long running, small MEM\n2. client immediately sends curr loc & server performs following task in conn handler fn\na. update user loc in loc cache\nb. saves loc i na variable of the conn handler for subsequent calcs\nc. load all user's friends from DB\nd. make a batched request ot the loc cache to fetch all locs. becoz TTL was set on\n    each entry that matches inactivity, we can tell if friend is on/off line\ne. for each loc returned by cache, server computes the dist. between the user & friend\n    if its within range, it will return client with the (lat,lng,timestmap)\nf. for each  friend, server subscribes to the friend's channel in the redis pub/sub server\n(creation of new channel is cheap, user subscribes to all active & inactive friends; inactive friends\n    only take up a smalle amt of MEM on redis pub/sub server but will not consumer any CPU/IO (since no updates))",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "bO07o5jw_Aj9OcZvmG5cb",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -362.16102922992195,
      "y": 143.15558095531952,
      "width": 626.4595947265625,
      "height": 200,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3L",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1225203296,
      "version": 518,
      "versionNonce": 834391968,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771555073820,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "usually steps for interview:\n- clarify what are we solving here?\n- how do we want to measure this success?\n- if we have a few things, can we prioritize the more impt thing?\n   (i.e. for finding nearby friends maybe\n        we dont want to make it too dynamic\n        by allowing variable ranges of nearby)\n- what system should we focus on?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "usually steps for interview:\n- clarify what are we solving here?\n- how do we want to measure this success?\n- if we have a few things, can we prioritize the more impt thing?\n   (i.e. for finding nearby friends maybe\n        we dont want to make it too dynamic\n        by allowing variable ranges of nearby)\n- what system should we focus on?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "lBD2F-u3NWByCl5y1l5w4",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1294.7614539125138,
      "y": 4221.379645610198,
      "width": 1107.2791748046875,
      "height": 2075,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3M",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2128170912,
      "version": 3750,
      "versionNonce": 584757856,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771559177899,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Redis pub/ sub:\n- used as routing layer to direct message (loc updates) from 1 to another\n- lightweight to create new channels\n- channel created when someone subscribes to it (if no subscriber, publisher msg is dropped)\n\nchannel creation:\n    - hash table\n    - linked list\n=> this tracks subscribers\n=> no update, no CPU used\n\nsteps:\n1. assign a unqiue channel to evry user who uses the nearby friends feature\n- on init, subscribe to each friend's channel, whether their online or not\n- this simplifies design on BE as BE does not need to handle subscribing to friend's\nchannel when online, & unsubscribing when offline\n\n2. trade off is more MEM used, but unlikely to be bottleneck\n    => trading higher MEM for simpler architecture is worth it here\n\nhow many redis pud/ sub servers do we need?\nMEM:\n- assume a channel is assigned to each user\n- 100mil channels\n- assume each user has ~100 friends\n- uses about 20 bytes of pointers in the internal hash table & linked list to track each subscriber\n- 100 mil * (20 bytes * 100 friends) = 200 GB\n=> will need about 2 redis pub/ sub servers to hold all channels\n\nCPU:\n- prev calc millions of updates per second to subscribers\n- redis server cant handle load => assume that modern redis server with gigabit network\n                                        handles about 100_000 subscribers per sec\n14 mil / 100_000 = 140 redis servers\n- bottleneck is the CPU usage\n\n- channels are indpt, easy to shard base on publisher's Ids\n- becoz of sharding, we need to use consistent hashing to route users to specific shards\n    - go into detail as servers go down from time to time\n    - include server discovery component (zookeep / etcd) => this keeps info about the hash ring\n        key: /config/pub_sub_ring\n        val: [\"p_1\", \"p_2\", ...]\n        - key stores hash ring of all active redis pub/ sub servers in service discovery component\n        - helps determine which redis server to find the channel\n        - gives clients ability to subscribe to any udpates to the \"value\" (redis pub/ sub servers)\n\nserver discovery & update:\n- when loc update receive\n- WS server consults hash ring to determine redis pub/ sub server to write to\n- src of truth is stored in service discovery, WS server can keep this hash ring in mem (cache)\n    BUT subscribes to any updates on the key value \n- WS then publishes loc update to the user's channel on that redis pub/sub server\n*subscribing to a channel uses this same mechanism\n\nScaling redis cluster itself:\n- scale up & down daily base on traffic patterns? \n\n1. msgs sent on pub/ sub channel are not persisted in MEM or disk\n    are sent to all subscribers & removed immediately\n    if no subscribers, jsut dropped\n    => stateless data\n2. but state is stored for channels\n    subscriber list for each channel is key  piece of state\n    - if channel is moved/ added/ removed, every subscriber to that channel\n        must know about the move\n    - this is so they can subscribe to the same channel, on different servers\n\nthus, redis cluster is treated more like a stateful cluster\n- stateful clusters, scaling up or down requires more oeprational overhead\n- usually over-provisioned to make sure if can handle daily peak traffic\n    with some comfortable head room to avoid unnecessary resizing\n\nwhen scaling is required:\n- consistent hashing (for redis shards)\n    - allows subscribers (servers) to constantly be assigne to the same servers/ find users on consistent servers\n    - when add / remove\n        - there will be mass resubscription events/ mass reconnections\n        - loc updates / messages might be missed by clients\n        - coz of potential interruptions resizing shld be done at lowest usage of day\n\nOld: [\"p_1\", \"p_2\", \"p_3\", \"p_4\"]\nNew: [\"p_1_new\", \"p_2\", \"p-_3\", \"p_4\"]\nserver_id = get_server(hash(channel_name)) # the server_id changes according to what was updated",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Redis pub/ sub:\n- used as routing layer to direct message (loc updates) from 1 to another\n- lightweight to create new channels\n- channel created when someone subscribes to it (if no subscriber, publisher msg is dropped)\n\nchannel creation:\n    - hash table\n    - linked list\n=> this tracks subscribers\n=> no update, no CPU used\n\nsteps:\n1. assign a unqiue channel to evry user who uses the nearby friends feature\n- on init, subscribe to each friend's channel, whether their online or not\n- this simplifies design on BE as BE does not need to handle subscribing to friend's\nchannel when online, & unsubscribing when offline\n\n2. trade off is more MEM used, but unlikely to be bottleneck\n    => trading higher MEM for simpler architecture is worth it here\n\nhow many redis pud/ sub servers do we need?\nMEM:\n- assume a channel is assigned to each user\n- 100mil channels\n- assume each user has ~100 friends\n- uses about 20 bytes of pointers in the internal hash table & linked list to track each subscriber\n- 100 mil * (20 bytes * 100 friends) = 200 GB\n=> will need about 2 redis pub/ sub servers to hold all channels\n\nCPU:\n- prev calc millions of updates per second to subscribers\n- redis server cant handle load => assume that modern redis server with gigabit network\n                                        handles about 100_000 subscribers per sec\n14 mil / 100_000 = 140 redis servers\n- bottleneck is the CPU usage\n\n- channels are indpt, easy to shard base on publisher's Ids\n- becoz of sharding, we need to use consistent hashing to route users to specific shards\n    - go into detail as servers go down from time to time\n    - include server discovery component (zookeep / etcd) => this keeps info about the hash ring\n        key: /config/pub_sub_ring\n        val: [\"p_1\", \"p_2\", ...]\n        - key stores hash ring of all active redis pub/ sub servers in service discovery component\n        - helps determine which redis server to find the channel\n        - gives clients ability to subscribe to any udpates to the \"value\" (redis pub/ sub servers)\n\nserver discovery & update:\n- when loc update receive\n- WS server consults hash ring to determine redis pub/ sub server to write to\n- src of truth is stored in service discovery, WS server can keep this hash ring in mem (cache)\n    BUT subscribes to any updates on the key value \n- WS then publishes loc update to the user's channel on that redis pub/sub server\n*subscribing to a channel uses this same mechanism\n\nScaling redis cluster itself:\n- scale up & down daily base on traffic patterns? \n\n1. msgs sent on pub/ sub channel are not persisted in MEM or disk\n    are sent to all subscribers & removed immediately\n    if no subscribers, jsut dropped\n    => stateless data\n2. but state is stored for channels\n    subscriber list for each channel is key  piece of state\n    - if channel is moved/ added/ removed, every subscriber to that channel\n        must know about the move\n    - this is so they can subscribe to the same channel, on different servers\n\nthus, redis cluster is treated more like a stateful cluster\n- stateful clusters, scaling up or down requires more oeprational overhead\n- usually over-provisioned to make sure if can handle daily peak traffic\n    with some comfortable head room to avoid unnecessary resizing\n\nwhen scaling is required:\n- consistent hashing (for redis shards)\n    - allows subscribers (servers) to constantly be assigne to the same servers/ find users on consistent servers\n    - when add / remove\n        - there will be mass resubscription events/ mass reconnections\n        - loc updates / messages might be missed by clients\n        - coz of potential interruptions resizing shld be done at lowest usage of day\n\nOld: [\"p_1\", \"p_2\", \"p_3\", \"p_4\"]\nNew: [\"p_1_new\", \"p_2\", \"p-_3\", \"p_4\"]\nserver_id = get_server(hash(channel_name)) # the server_id changes according to what was updated",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
